input: England hopeful over Jones  England are hopeful that Simon Jones will be fit for the Boxing Day Test against South Africa despite going down with a stomach bug.
The Glamorgan paceman left Friday practice session early to return to the team hotel.
"He is got a slight bug but he had a little bit of a bowl, and I am sure he will be fine for the Test," captain Michael Vaughan commented.
Jones took 4-39 in the first Test to help England to a seven-wicket victory.
And coach Duncan Fletcher hopes he will return to bowling at express pace after a lengthy rehabilitation from a knee injury.
Jones has bowled with reduced speed since tearing a cruciate ligament at the start of the 2002/03 Ashes tour.
"Now he is got this confidence he can probably up the speed a little bit," Fletcher told BBC Sport.
"And if he can do that we have got a strong bowling unit there."
The Welshman showed glimpses of his former self during the recent one-day series in Zimbabwe.
"There were a few balls he got over 140 [kph - 87.5 mph] where he was just trying himself out," Fletcher continued.
"And if he can get back up there he will be back to being that shock bowler.
"He is hardly played any first-class cricket - he is hardly played any games for Glamorgan, he is only played a few Tests for us."
Should Jones fail to recover in time for the second Test, Lancashire James Anderson would be the obvious replacement.
